==English==

===Alternative forms===
*[[rub salt in someone's wounds]], [[rub salt into the wounds]]

===Etymology===
Derived from the stingingly painful sensation of table salt deliberately being rubbed into an open, bleeding wound, as for torture, interrogation, etc.

===Verb===
{{infl|en|verb|head=[[rub]] [[salt in the wound]]}}

# {{idiomatic}} To make an injury feel worse.

====Usage notes====
* For {{term|rub}}, one can substitute verbs such as {{term|add}}, {{term|pour}}, {{term|put}}, possibly requiring a change in the preposition {{term|in}}.
* See [[salt in the wound]] for variations in that portion of the expression.

====Synonyms====
* [[add insult to injury]]
* [[kick someone when they are down]]

